This rifle is the descendant of the British Lee Enfield chambered in .303, and was in fact manufactured with many of the same machines but built in the Ishapore factory in India. These rifles saw action throughout much of the Cold War, and helped to defend Indian Province from both China and Pakistan. This rifle come with both a great history and:-A replacement synthetic Monte Carlo Stock in Black.-Matching numbers on the Receiver, Front site post shroud, and the magazine which is usually lost.-1 Detachable magazine with a 12 round capacity.-The original war scarred walnut stock.-and 60+ rounds of 7.62 x 51 (NATO)* This rifle is not without its share of damage though it is entirely cosmetic and shown in the pictures above, though they add to the appeal and patina of a true war rifle. The firearm functions flawlessly, the bolt chambers, fires, and extracts rounds smoothly, and quickly. The weight is more balanced than most of the surplus rifles of its day, and with the smooth bolt it is possible to make accurate follow up shots with little difficulty. The bore is in excellent condition and will consistently drop a pop can at 100 yards or a deer out of your favorite blind.
